Digit Recognizer

Ming Ming Zhang

Abstract

In this excercise, we use multi-class classification algorithms such as one-vs-all logistic regression and regularized single hidden layer neural networks to predict handwritten digits. Each image is 28 \(\times\) 28 pixels grayscale from digit 0 to 9. The dataset is a subset of MNIST available on here.

Since the purpose of this excercise is to learn and implement some algorithms, we will use PCA with 99% of variance retained to speed up learning algorithms. The visualization of a subset of original data and of PCA transformed data are provided.

The dataset will be divided into 3 parts: 60% for training, 20% for cross-validation and the rest of 20% for test set. Since the label classes is uniformly distributed, we will use accuracy for evaluation metric. The results are summarized as follows.

res = data.frame(Model=c("One-vs-all logistic regression", "Single hidden layer neural networks with 50 units"),
                 "Regularized Parameter"=c(0, 0.3),
                 Accuracy=c(0.810, 0.921))
res

The learning curve of one-vs-all logistic regression shows high bias as the number of training examples increases. So we choose the regularized parameter to be 0. On the other hand, the learning curve for neural networks with 50 units indicates high variance and low bias. We regularize the neural networks and obtain 0.921 accuracy on the test set. It is possible to get higher or perfect accuracies by using the original data or training the neural network for more units and iterations.

Note that all algorithms mentioned here are implemented in R.

The data

digits = read.csv("~/Downloads/Data/digit-recognizer/train.csv")
#submit = read.csv("~/Downloads/Data/digit-recognizer/test.csv") # Kaggle's submission
#submit$label = NA
#XY = rbind(digits, submit)
# Denote 0 digit by 10 to avoid indexing problem, the rest digits are denoted the same as before
digits$label[digits$label==0] = 10
#XY = as.matrix(XY)
XY = as.matrix(digits)
dim(XY)
[1] 42000   785
set.seed(123)
idx = sample(1:nrow(XY))
XY = XY[idx,]
ratioTrain = 0.6
ratioVal = 0.2
ratioTest = 0.2
XY_train = splitData(XY, ratioTrain, ratioVal, ratioTest)[[1]]
X_train = XY_train[,-1]
y_train = XY_train[,1]
XY_val = splitData(XY, ratioTrain, ratioVal, ratioTest)[[2]]
X_val = XY_val[,-1]
y_val = XY_val[,1]
XY_test = splitData(XY, ratioTrain, ratioVal, ratioTest)[[3]]
X_test = XY_test[,-1]
y_test = XY_test[,1]

Note that the label has 10 classes which are uniformly distributed. So we will use accuracy for the evaluation metric.

$figure

With all features, the one-vs-all logistic regression runs slowly. Its learning curve took about 10 mins. So we will use PCA to speed up the learning process.

PCA

PCA = pca(X_train)
U = PCA$U
D = PCA$D
p = 0.99
K = selectNumComponent(D, p)
K

[1] 330
Z_train = projectData(X_train, U, K)
Z_val = projectData(X_val, U, K)
Z_test = projectData(X_test, U, K)
library(EBImage)
L = list()
for (i in 1:100) {
  x_i = matrix(X_train[i,], nrow = sqrt(ncol(X_train)), ncol = sqrt(ncol(X_train)), byrow = T)
  L[[i]] = x_i
}
img = combine(L[1:100])
display(img, method = "raster", all = T)

X_train_rec = recoverData(Z_train, U, K)
L1 = list()
for (i in 1:100) {
  x_i = matrix(X_train_rec[i,], nrow = sqrt(ncol(X_train_rec)), ncol = sqrt(ncol(X_train_rec)), byrow = T)
  L1[[i]] = x_i
}
img_rec = combine(L1[1:100])
display(img_rec, method = "raster", all = T)

With dimensionality reduction (99% of variance retained), it took about 4 mins. However, its error increased. Note that the above learning curve shows high variance and high bias.

num_labels = 10
